    {
      "id": "odin-root",
      "title": "Odin Overview",
      "node_type": "root",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "Odin is a systems language world centered on explicit declarations, structured data, and pragmatic runtime patterns.",
        "Why": "This root node anchors the first-pass learning route through the world.",
        "Example": "package main\n\nimport \"core:fmt\"\n\nmain :: proc() {\n    state := State.Idle\n    fmt.println(state)\n}",
        "Pitfall": "Do not treat every edge as equal. The connection layers intentionally mean different things.",
        "Signals": "Gradual = learning order. Conceptual = mental model. Usage = common co-usage."
      },
      "content_data": "Root overview for the Odin language dataset.",
      "tags": [
        "group:syntax"
      ],
      "weight": 1.55,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "odin-root-frame",
          "title": "World reading frame",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "The Odin root is not syntax itself. It is the map legend for how to read the three connection lenses.",
            "Why": "If the learner misses this, the graph turns into one undifferentiated mesh.",
            "Example": "Start here, then switch between gradual for order and conceptual for understanding.",
            "Pitfall": "Treating all edges as if they mean the same thing.",
            "Signals": "Parent = Odin Overview."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for reading the world itself.",
          "tags": [
            "group:syntax"
          ],
          "weight": 0.84,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "package",
      "title": "package",
      "node_type": "grammar",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "Declares the package scope for a file.",
        "Why": "Package layout is one of the first structural ideas to understand.",
        "Example": "package core",
        "Pitfall": "Mixing package intent and import intent makes the module boundary harder to reason about.",
        "Signals": "Usually appears with import and top-level declarations."
      },
      "content_data": "Package declaration in Odin.",
      "tags": [
        "group:syntax"
      ],
      "weight": 1.25,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "package-boundary-cue",
          "title": "Package boundary cue",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "The package line tells you what logical space the file belongs to before any declaration is read.",
            "Why": "It frames every later name as belonging to a module boundary.",
            "Example": "Read package first, then ask what declarations live inside it.",
            "Pitfall": "Seeing package as a decorative header instead of a scope decision.",
            "Signals": "Parent = package."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for package.",
          "tags": [
            "group:syntax"
          ],
          "weight": 0.82,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "import",
      "title": "import",
      "node_type": "grammar",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "Brings external packages or modules into scope.",
        "Why": "Imports are where package boundaries become useful rather than abstract.",
        "Example": "import \"core:fmt\"\nimport math \"core:math\"",
        "Pitfall": "A learner can read import syntax without yet understanding why package boundaries matter.",
        "Signals": "Connects strongly to package and procedure-level usage."
      },
      "content_data": "Import statement and package access.",
      "tags": [
        "group:syntax",
        "group:runtime"
      ],
      "weight": 1.18,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "import-dependency-entry",
          "title": "Dependency entry point",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "Import is the moment external capability crosses into the file.",
            "Why": "It explains where later procedure calls or types actually come from.",
            "Example": "When you see import fmt, read later fmt usage as crossing a package boundary.",
            "Pitfall": "Memorizing syntax without tracking dependency origin.",
            "Signals": "Parent = import."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for import.",
          "tags": [
            "group:syntax",
            "group:runtime"
          ],
          "weight": 0.82,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "declaration",
      "title": "declaration",
      "node_type": "concept",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "Top-level declarations introduce named entities such as variables, constants, procedures, and types.",
        "Why": "It is the bridge from syntax into the rest of the language surface.",
        "Example": "State :: enum {\n    Idle,\n    Busy,\n    Failed,\n}\n\nmain :: proc() {\n    current := State.Idle\n}",
        "Pitfall": "Thinking in isolated syntax forms instead of one declaration space makes the map harder to navigate.",
        "Signals": "This is a bridge node between the syntax and declarations groups."
      },
      "content_data": "Top-level declaration model.",
      "tags": [
        "group:syntax",
        "group:declarations"
      ],
      "weight": 1.32,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "declaration-name-surface",
          "title": "Name introduction surface",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "Declaration is the shared surface where names enter the file and become available to the rest of the graph.",
            "Why": "This is the hinge between syntax and meaningful language objects.",
            "Example": "Variables, constants, procedures, and types are all declaration outcomes.",
            "Pitfall": "Thinking each form is isolated instead of seeing one declaration space.",
            "Signals": "Parent = declaration."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for declaration.",
          "tags": [
            "group:syntax",
            "group:declarations"
          ],
          "weight": 0.84,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "variable",
      "title": "variable",
      "node_type": "concept",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "A mutable named value.",
        "Why": "Variables are usually the first declaration learners reach for.",
        "Example": "count := 0\ncount += 1",
        "Pitfall": "Do not collapse variables and constants into the same mental slot.",
        "Signals": "Variable usage often appears near procedures and pointers."
      },
      "content_data": "Mutable storage in Odin.",
      "tags": [
        "group:declarations"
      ],
      "weight": 1.15,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "variable-mutation-pressure",
          "title": "Mutation pressure",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "A variable is the point where runtime change is allowed to enter the design.",
            "Why": "It is useful because it separates changing state from fixed intent.",
            "Example": "Use a variable when later procedure steps are expected to rewrite the value.",
            "Pitfall": "Choosing variable by habit instead of because change is required.",
            "Signals": "Parent = variable."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for variable.",
          "tags": [
            "group:declarations"
          ],
          "weight": 0.8,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "constant",
      "title": "constant",
      "node_type": "concept",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "An immutable named value.",
        "Why": "Constants separate stable compile-time intent from mutable runtime state.",
        "Example": "MAX_ITEMS :: 64\nDEFAULT_STATE :: State.Idle",
        "Pitfall": "Overusing variables where a constant communicates intent more clearly.",
        "Signals": "Frequently connects conceptually to enum and declaration."
      },
      "content_data": "Immutable declaration in Odin.",
      "tags": [
        "group:declarations"
      ],
      "weight": 1.1,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "constant-intent-lock",
          "title": "Intent lock",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "A constant says the value itself is part of the design intent, not part of runtime churn.",
            "Why": "That makes later enum or switch logic easier to read.",
            "Example": "A fixed size or sentinel value reads more clearly as a constant.",
            "Pitfall": "Using mutable storage for values that should communicate stability.",
            "Signals": "Parent = constant."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for constant.",
          "tags": [
            "group:declarations"
          ],
          "weight": 0.8,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "proc",
      "title": "proc",
      "node_type": "grammar",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "Procedure declaration and callable behavior unit.",
        "Why": "Procedures are where declarations become active behavior.",
        "Example": "main :: proc() {\n    fmt.println(\"hello\")\n}",
        "Pitfall": "Reading proc only as syntax instead of as the center of runtime patterns.",
        "Signals": "Strong bridge node into runtime and usage links."
      },
      "content_data": "Procedure declaration and execution unit.",
      "tags": [
        "group:declarations",
        "group:runtime"
      ],
      "weight": 1.28,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "proc-behavior-center",
          "title": "Behavior center",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "Procedure nodes are where the rest of the graph becomes active behavior instead of static structure.",
            "Why": "Many usage relationships radiate from here.",
            "Example": "Imports, data shapes, context, and cleanup all become meaningful inside procedures.",
            "Pitfall": "Reading proc as just syntax punctuation.",
            "Signals": "Parent = proc."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for proc.",
          "tags": [
            "group:declarations",
            "group:runtime"
          ],
          "weight": 0.84,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "struct",
      "title": "struct",
      "node_type": "concept",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "Structured product type for named fields.",
        "Why": "Structs are central to data layout and procedure interaction.",
        "Example": "User :: struct {\n    id: int,\n    name: string,\n}",
        "Pitfall": "Seeing struct only as storage instead of as a design boundary used by procedures and pointers.",
        "Signals": "Strongly related to pointer and proc."
      },
      "content_data": "Structured data type in Odin.",
      "tags": [
        "group:data"
      ],
      "weight": 1.2,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "struct-shape-contract",
          "title": "Shape and contract",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "A struct is not only stored data. It is a contract for how procedures expect data to be shaped.",
            "Why": "That is why structs bridge data and runtime patterns.",
            "Example": "A User struct is meaningful because procedures consume or mutate that shape.",
            "Pitfall": "Treating struct as a bag of fields with no behavioral boundary.",
            "Signals": "Parent = struct."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for struct.",
          "tags": [
            "group:data"
          ],
          "weight": 0.82,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "enum",
      "title": "enum",
      "node_type": "concept",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "Finite named set of values.",
        "Why": "Enums tighten state expression and work well with constants and switches.",
        "Example": "State :: enum {\n    Idle,\n    Busy,\n    Failed,\n}",
        "Pitfall": "Treating enum values like unstructured literals reduces clarity.",
        "Signals": "Often conceptually near constants."
      },
      "content_data": "Finite named states.",
      "tags": [
        "group:data",
        "group:declarations"
      ],
      "weight": 1.05,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "enum-state-vocabulary",
          "title": "State vocabulary",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "An enum defines the allowed named states so the rest of the program stops speaking in loose literals.",
            "Why": "It gives state changes a disciplined vocabulary.",
            "Example": "Idle, Busy, and Failed read as a designed state space instead of random strings or numbers.",
            "Pitfall": "Using ad hoc literals where an explicit state set is the real concept.",
            "Signals": "Parent = enum."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for enum.",
          "tags": [
            "group:data",
            "group:declarations"
          ],
          "weight": 0.82,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "array",
      "title": "array",
      "node_type": "concept",
      "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
      "note_fields": {
        "Summary": "Fixed-length contiguous sequence.",
        "Why": "Arrays establish the data-layout baseline before slices.",
        "Example": "values := [4]int{1, 2, 3, 4}",
        "Pitfall": "Jumping to slices before understanding the fixed container underneath them.",
        "Signals": "Gradual links should reach slice from here."
      },
      "content_data": "Fixed-size collection.",
      "tags": [
        "group:data"
      ],
      "weight": 1.12,
      "layer_membership": [
        "core-map"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "sublayer_nodes": [
        {
          "id": "array-fixed-layout",
          "title": "Fixed layout intuition",
          "node_type": "concept",
          "note_type_id": "odin-concept",
          "note_fields": {
            "Summary": "Array is the stable memory-layout picture behind later sequence abstractions.",
            "Why": "If this stays clear, slices become easier to reason about.",
            "Example": "Think contiguous fixed slots first, then add views over them.",
            "Pitfall": "Jumping straight to slice convenience with no memory model.",
            "Signals": "Parent = array."
          },
          "content_data": "Sublayer note for array.",
          "tags": [
            "group:data"
          ],
          "weight": 0.8,
          "layer_membership": [
            "core-map"
          ],
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
